  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Humanitarian Assistance to Rohingya and Host Communities in Bangladesh</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On 22 March 2021, a massive fire broke out in the Camps 8W, 9, 10 and 8E housing Rohingya refugees in the Cox&#x2019;s Bazar District, Bangladesh. All of these camps are in IOM&#x2019;s site management area of responsibility. Teams on the ground said that the scale and intensity of this latest fire was unlike anything seen before in the camps. According to reports, while efforts were made to bring the situation under control, the fire raged through the camps and only slowed down once it reached the main roads, slopes, canals and rice fields. The fire consumed the shelters and personal belongings of thousands of Rohingya refugee families and essential facilities in the camps. With the key objective of ensuring continuity of lifesaving services for the Rohingya refugees affected by the fire, IOM is focusing and upscaling efforts on shelter/non-food items, health, water, sanitation and hygiene, protection, site management and site development and site maintenance and engineering project.</narrative>
  </description>
